				\begin{document}$${{{{\rm{Fe}}}}}_{4+{{{\rm{x}}}}}{{{{\rm{S}}}}}_{3}\left({{{\rm{solid}}}}\right)=2{{{\rm{FeS}}}}\left({{{\rm{solid}}}}\right)+{{{{\rm{Fe}}}}}_{2+{{{\rm{x}}}}}{{{\rm{S}}}}({{{\rm{liquid}}}})$$\end{document}Fe4+xS3solid=2FeSsolid+Fe2+xS(liquid)17. The Fe4+xS3 synthesized in this study coexists with Fe-S liquid at 1640 K and 27 GPa, indicating a melting temperature higher than this. An extrapolation of the melting curve to the pressure at the center of the Martian core (~40 GPa), indicates that Fe4+xS3 is stable up to approximately 1970(±105) K (Supplementary Fig. 4). This relatively refractory behavior of Fe4+xS3 underlines the potential for it to form planetary inner cores.
